#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Serialize the whole *land-on-main* critical section across parallel agents.

WHY THIS EXISTS
===============
The render gate (``tests/app/integration/conftest.py``) serializes the render
*runs* but not the *merges*. So agents would validate SPECULATIVELY in parallel —
the render-gate queue grows 10+ deep — then race to ``git merge --ff-only``.
Whoever loses the race has ``main`` move under them with an ``rtt/app/`` change, so
the green render run they just finished no longer validates the exact merged state.
The fix is a single-holder **merge lock** that covers the whole
``rebase main → render gate → ff-merge`` critical section, so only the lock-holder
validates-and-merges at a time, the render-gate queue stays ~1 deep, and the
holder validates the EXACT state it lands. Throughput is unchanged (the render
gate is still 1-slot) — the *wasted speculative validation* disappears.

THE HOLE WE CLOSED, AND THE LEASE REDESIGN
==========================================
The first version wrapped one ``bash -c 'rebase; gate; ff-merge'`` and released
when that command exited. It held the lock across all three steps, so the gate was
never wasted — BUT a conflicting ``git rebase main`` (``main`` moved while we were
queued; the wait can be 400s+) can't be resolved inside a single wrapped command:
``set -e`` exits, the lock releases, and the *entire long queue-wait is burned
before ever reaching the gate*. Under constant contention that thrashes.

So the lock now also exposes **subcommands** that hold it CONTINUOUSLY across many
independent tool calls, backed by a detached, lease-renewing **holder daemon**::

    bin/with-merge-lock acquire     # blocks ONCE until held; spawns the daemon, returns
    git rebase main                 # main is frozen (we hold it) — resolve conflicts at leisure
    bin/with-merge-lock renew       # before the gate: extend the hold, verify we still hold
    .venv/bin/python -m pytest -q   # the render gate, on the EXACT state we will land
    bin/with-merge-lock renew       # verify we STILL hold (aborts if we lost it)
    git -C <main-checkout> merge --ff-only <branch>     # guaranteed: nothing moved
    bin/with-merge-lock release     # free it for the next agent

The legacy single-command form still works for back-compat and CI::

    bin/with-merge-lock bash -c 'set -e; git rebase main; pytest -q; git merge --ff-only ...'

ARCHITECTURE (and the failure modes it was hardened against)
============================================================
Two artifacts live in ``$GATE_DIR`` (default ``/tmp/rtt-merge-gate.d/``):

* **Fairness tickets** ``<arrival_ns>-<pid>`` (empty files) — FIFO *ordering only*,
  identical in format to the render gate and to this lock's previous version, so
  old and new versions interoperate during a rollout. ``arrival_ns`` is fixed at
  arrival (FIFO, fair, no starvation). A ticket is live iff its PID is alive AND it
  was touched within ``ABS_MAX`` (live owners ``os.utime`` their ticket every poll;
  the mtime bound finally reclaims a *PID-reused* stale ticket, which pure
  PID-liveness can NEVER reclaim — we have observed those wedge the lock in the wild).

* **The holder marker** ``.holder`` (a dotfile, so the ``<ns>-<pid>`` ticket parser
  in BOTH versions and the render gate ignore it). This — NOT ticket order — is the
  real mutual-exclusion authority. ``time.time_ns()`` is only microsecond-granular
  on this macOS box, so ``(ns,pid)`` is not a reliable total order (~8.5% collisions);
  the marker is claimed by an **atomic ``O_EXCL`` create**, so two colliding-ns
  front-runners can't both hold — exactly one wins the create. Contents (atomically
  rewritten): ``{epoch, daemon_pid, lease_expiry, ...}``. ``epoch`` is a unique claim
  id (``time_ns`` at claim); the owning daemon and ``renew``/``release`` match BOTH
  ``epoch`` and ``daemon_pid``, so PID reuse alone can't impersonate a holder.

Holder daemon (detached via ``start_new_session``; survives the spawning tool call,
the parent bash, and SIGHUP):
  * Renews the marker lease every ``RENEW`` seconds (loop-driven, NOT signal-driven —
    PEP 475 means a signal does not wake ``time.sleep``, so lease freshness must not
    depend on signals).
  * **Self-fences**: if it ever finds wall-clock past its own ``lease_expiry`` it
    EXITS without rewriting the marker. Takeover by anyone else is only permitted at
    ``lease_expiry + LEASE_GRACE``. So a stale marker has NO live writer by the time
    it can be taken over — the renew-resurrects-a-released-marker race is impossible.
  * Verifies it still owns the marker (epoch+pid) each loop; if taken over, it exits
    WITHOUT re-creating anything (there is deliberately NO ticket/marker "re-stake" —
    re-staking a lost lock was the core double-holder bug in the lease-on-ticket
    design).
  * Backstops, four non-overlapping layers: PID-death (fast — daemon crashed) ·
    lease+grace (daemon hung but alive) · ``last_renew + HARD_GAP`` self-exit (agent
    abandoned the hold / forgot ``release``) · an un-bumpable absolute cap, ``ABS_MAX``
    measured as WALL-CLOCK ``hold-age`` from the marker ``epoch`` (the claim time,
    fixed for the life of the hold and preserved across every lease renew). The cap is
    enforced on BOTH sides so it cannot depend on the holder cooperating: the daemon
    self-exits at ``hold-age >= ABS_MAX``, AND a front waiter independently reclaims a
    marker at ``hold-age >= ABS_MAX + GRACE`` (``_over_abs_cap`` → ``_marker_stale``),
    even if that daemon is alive and still renewing its lease. The old cap was monotonic
    from ``birth`` and enforced ONLY inside the daemon's own loop, so a wedged-but-alive
    daemon (monotonic stalled across a macOS system sleep, a large ``TTL`` override in
    its env, or a respawn that reset ``birth``) could renew its lease forever and NO
    waiter could ever reclaim it — observed pinning the lock ~55 min in the wild. Wall-
    clock ``hold-age`` is sleep-proof and shared by every process, so daemon self-exit
    and external takeover read the same number. The PID-death layer is enforced two
    ways: a front waiter takes over a stale marker, AND ``_scan`` / ``_reap_dead_marker``
    removes a dead-PID marker on *every* poll regardless of queue position — so a
    leaked/PID-reused ticket stuck ahead in the FIFO can no longer pin a crashed holder's
    marker in place until ``WAIT_MAX``.
  * Signal handlers ONLY set a flag / stamp a time / poke a self-pipe (to make the
    sleep interruptible) — never touch files — so a SIGTERM can't interrupt a marker
    rewrite mid-flight; all file mutation happens in the loop body.
  * ``watch_parent`` (legacy mode only): also exits if the wrapping process dies, for
    today's fast SIGKILL recovery. Subcommand mode leaves it unset (the Claude session
    is unwatchable) and relies on ``HARD_GAP`` for abandonment recovery.

Correctness backstop of last resort: even if a pathology ever produces two
simultaneous "holders", ``git merge --ff-only`` is an atomic ref CAS — at most one
ff succeeds, the other fails cleanly, and ``main`` is NEVER corrupted or
double-landed. The lock's job is to make a wasted gate RARE; ``--ff-only`` makes a
race SAFE.

A deliberately NON-feature: ``acquire`` does NOT touch ``git config`` / rerere.
``rerere.enabled`` is already on repo-wide and records resolutions you still review;
flipping ``rerere.autoupdate`` on globally would let a textually-identical conflict
preimage recorded on a DIFFERENT branch auto-stage a wrong resolution into your
held-lock rebase (the ``rr-cache`` is shared across all worktrees). So we leave git
config alone.

Env knobs:
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_DIR``    ticket/marker directory (default ``/tmp/rtt-merge-gate.d``)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_WAIT``   max seconds to queue before giving up (default 3600; on
                              timeout we FAIL — we never "proceed unlocked", which
                              would be a routine double-holder path)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_LEASE``  marker lease seconds (default 300)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_GRACE``  extra seconds before a stale marker may be taken over (default 60)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_RENEW``  daemon renew interval (default 15)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_GAP``    self-exit if no agent ``renew`` within this many seconds (default 900)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_TTL``    absolute, un-bumpable hold cap as wall-clock hold-age from
                              the claim epoch; daemon self-exits at TTL, a waiter reclaims
                              at TTL+GRACE regardless of lease/liveness (default 2400)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_READY``  seconds ``acquire`` waits for its daemon to take the lock (default 30)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_PROGRESS_FILE`` opt-in: path the held gate stamps as it advances; the
                              holder daemon reclaims the lock if it goes stale (see below)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_PROGRESS`` seconds of NO gate progress before work-progress reclaim
                              fires (default 300; only active when PROGRESS_FILE is set)
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_NOLOCK`` set to ``1`` to run the wrapped command without the lock
  * ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_DEBUG``  set to ``1`` to log daemon activity to ``$GATE_DIR/.daemon-<pid>.log``

Pure stdlib, Python 3.7+ (runs under the shebang ``python3`` = system 3.9 here; it
must NOT depend on the repo ``.venv``). Single machine, single wall clock.
"""

import atexit
import errno
import hashlib
import json
import os
import select
import signal
import subprocess
import sys
import time

# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Configuration
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
_DIR = os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_DIR", "/tmp/rtt-merge-gate.d")
_WAIT_MAX = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_WAIT", "3600"))
_LEASE = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_LEASE", "300"))
_GRACE = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_GRACE", "60"))
_RENEW = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_RENEW", "15"))
_GAP = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_GAP", "900"))
_ABS_MAX = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_TTL", "2400"))
# Manual `evict` floor: the minimum hold age at which an agent may force-reclaim a holder it
# has CONFIRMED is wedged. Below this, evict refuses (a healthy land can legitimately hold the
# lock this long), so it can never be abused to jump a moving queue. Sits below the automatic
# abs-cap reclaim (_ABS_MAX + _GRACE, ~41 min) so a human/agent need not wait that long on a
# visibly-stuck holder, but well above a normal/dogpiled land cycle.
_EVICT_MIN = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_EVICT", "1500"))
_READY = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_READY", "30"))
_DISABLED = os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_NOLOCK") == "1"
_DEBUG = os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_DEBUG") == "1"

# Work-progress reclaim (opt-in): when ``RTT_MERGE_PROGRESS_FILE`` names a file
# that the held render gate stamps as it advances (the conftest does this when the
# same env var is set), the holder daemon self-exits if that file goes stale for
# ``RTT_MERGE_GATE_PROGRESS`` seconds — freeing a WEDGED gate in minutes instead of
# waiting out ABS_MAX. Crucially this is keyed to REAL gate progress, NOT the agent's
# ``renew``: a crawling-but-progressing gate keeps the file fresh and is never
# reclaimed, while a timer-renewing agent can no longer keep a truly hung gate alive.
# Unset → the daemon behaves exactly as before (lease + GAP + ABS_MAX backstops only).
_PROGRESS_FILE = os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_PROGRESS_FILE") or None
_PROGRESS = int(os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_GATE_PROGRESS", "300"))

_POLL = 3            # seconds between FIFO-wait scans
_REPORT_EVERY = 15   # seconds between "still waiting" lines

_MARKER = os.path.join(_DIR, ".holder")
_SUBCOMMANDS = {"acquire", "renew", "release", "status", "evict", "__daemon"}


def _log(msg):
    sys.stderr.write("[merge-gate] %s\n" % msg)
    sys.stderr.flush()


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Low-level helpers (shared by every mode)
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
def _alive(pid):
    """True iff `pid` names a live process."""
    if pid <= 0:
        return False
    try:
        os.kill(pid, 0)
    except ProcessLookupError:
        return False
    except PermissionError:
        return True  # exists, just not ours to signal
    return True


def _write_atomic(path, text):
    """Write `text` to `path` atomically (temp in the same dir + os.replace), so a
    concurrent reader never sees a half-written or empty file."""
    tmp = "%s.tmp-%d-%d" % (path, os.getpid(), time.time_ns())
    with open(tmp, "w") as f:
        f.write(text)
        f.flush()
        os.fsync(f.fileno())
    os.replace(tmp, path)


def _read_json(path):
    """Return the parsed JSON dict at `path`, or None on any problem (missing,
    empty, mid-write garbage). Callers must treat None as 'no usable info'."""
    try:
        with open(path) as f:
            data = f.read()
    except OSError:
        return None
    if not data.strip():
        return None
    try:
        obj = json.loads(data)
    except ValueError:
        return None
    return obj if isinstance(obj, dict) else None


def _token():
    """Stable per-worktree identifier — which worktree's hold this is, so
    ``renew``/``release`` find their own daemon and a second ``acquire`` from the
    same worktree is idempotent. ``RTT_MERGE_LOCK_ID`` overrides it (distinct
    identities without distinct worktrees — used by the self-test and any
    non-git context). Otherwise the git worktree top-level (stable across subdirs
    and mid-rebase); falls back to realpath(cwd)."""
    explicit = os.environ.get("RTT_MERGE_LOCK_ID")
    if explicit:
        return hashlib.sha1(explicit.encode("utf-8")).hexdigest()[:16]
    root = None
    try:
        r = subprocess.run(
            ["git", "rev-parse", "--show-toplevel"],
            capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=10,
        )
        if r.returncode == 0:
            root = r.stdout.strip()
    except (OSError, subprocess.SubprocessError):
        root = None
    if not root:
        root = os.path.realpath(os.getcwd())
    return hashlib.sha1(root.encode("utf-8")).hexdigest()[:16]


def _state_path(token):
    return os.path.join(_DIR, ".state-%s" % token)


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Fairness tickets (FIFO ordering only — NOT the mutex)
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
def _scan():
    """Live tickets as ``(ns, pid, name)`` sorted FIFO. Also frees a DEAD-PID holder
    marker on the spot (``_reap_dead_marker``) so a crashed holder is reclaimed in
    seconds by ANY poller — not only by a waiter that reaches the front of the queue.
    Reclaims (removes) a ticket if:
      * its PID is dead (fast — the common crash case), OR
      * it belongs to the holder of a STALE marker (a hung-but-alive NEW holder: the
        marker lease, not the ticket, is the liveness signal, so clearing its ticket
        lets a waiter advance and take over within ~lease+grace rather than ABS_MAX), OR
      * its mtime is older than ABS_MAX (bounds the PID-reuse / leaked-ticket wedge that
        pure PID-liveness can never reclaim; this is the ONLY bound an OLD-version
        holder's ticket is subject to, since old holders have no marker — so it must
        stay long enough not to evict a legit old-version hold mid-gate).
    Live owners keep their ticket fresh with os.utime every poll, so only dead/defunct/
    leaked tickets are removed."""
    live = []
    now = time.time()
    m = _read_json(_MARKER)
    defunct_pid = None
    if m is not None and _marker_stale(m, now):
        try:
            defunct_pid = int(m.get("daemon_pid", 0)) or None
        except (TypeError, ValueError):
            defunct_pid = None
        # Free a DEAD-PID holder marker right now, regardless of where this caller sits
        # in the FIFO. Marker takeover otherwise only runs for a waiter that reaches the
        # front (idx == 0); a single leaked/PID-reused ticket ahead would then wedge the
        # dead marker in place for the full WAIT_MAX. A PID-alive (hung/reused) holder is
        # left untouched here, governed by the lease+grace path.
        _reap_dead_marker(m)
    try:
        names = os.listdir(_DIR)
    except OSError:
        return live
    for name in names:
        if name.startswith("."):
            continue  # marker, state, temp files — never tickets
        try:
            ns_s, pid_s = name.rsplit("-", 1)
            ns, pid = int(ns_s), int(pid_s)
        except ValueError:
            continue
        path = os.path.join(_DIR, name)
        dead = not _alive(pid)
        if not dead and defunct_pid is not None and pid == defunct_pid:
            dead = True  # holder of a stale marker — its ticket is defunct
        stale = False
        if not dead:
            try:
                stale = (now - os.path.getmtime(path)) > _ABS_MAX
            except OSError:
                stale = True
        if dead or stale:
            try:
                os.remove(path)
            except OSError:
                pass
        else:
            live.append((ns, pid, name))
    live.sort()
    return live


def _touch(path):
    try:
        os.utime(path, None)
    except OSError:
        pass


def _make_ticket(ns, pid):
    name = "%d-%d" % (ns, pid)
    path = os.path.join(_DIR, name)
    try:
        open(path, "x").close()
    except FileExistsError:
        pass
    except OSError:
        pass
    return name, path


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# The holder marker (the real mutual-exclusion authority)
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
def _hold_age(m, now=None):
    """Wall-clock seconds this marker has been held, measured from its claim `epoch`
    (a fixed ``time_ns`` stamped once when the hold began and preserved across every
    lease renew, so it does NOT reset when a daemon re-arms its lease — unlike the
    daemon's own monotonic ``birth``). Wall-clock, not monotonic, so it keeps advancing
    across a macOS system sleep. Returns None if the epoch is missing/unparseable."""
    if m is None:
        return None
    if now is None:
        now = time.time()
    try:
        epoch_ns = int(m.get("epoch", 0))
    except (TypeError, ValueError):
        return None
    if epoch_ns <= 0:
        return None
    return now - epoch_ns / 1e9


def _over_abs_cap(m, now=None):
    """True iff this hold has exceeded the absolute cap by more than GRACE — the
    EXTERNALLY-enforceable ceiling. A front waiter may reclaim such a marker regardless
    of lease freshness or daemon liveness, so a wedged-but-alive daemon that never
    self-exits (monotonic stall across system sleep, a large TTL override in its own
    env, or CPU starvation delaying its loop) can no longer pin the lock until WAIT_MAX.
    The +GRACE margin sits ABOVE the daemon's own ABS_MAX self-exit, so a cooperating
    daemon has already removed its marker before any waiter reaches this point."""
    age = _hold_age(m, now)
    return age is not None and age >= _ABS_MAX + _GRACE


def _marker_stale(m, now=None):
    """True iff marker dict `m` may be taken over: its hold blew the absolute cap, its
    daemon is dead, or its lease expired more than GRACE ago (by which point a live
    daemon has self-fenced). The abs-cap clause is what makes the cap enforceable from
    OUTSIDE the holder — reclaim no longer depends on the holder cooperating."""
    if m is None:
        return True
    if now is None:
        now = time.time()
    if _over_abs_cap(m, now):
        return True
    pid = m.get("daemon_pid", 0)
    if not _alive(int(pid) if pid else 0):
        return True
    return now >= float(m.get("lease_expiry", 0)) + _GRACE


def _marker_content(epoch, daemon_pid, token, lease_expiry):
    return json.dumps({
        "kind": "merge-holder",
        "epoch": epoch,
        "daemon_pid": daemon_pid,
        "token": token,
        "lease_expiry": lease_expiry,
    })


def _claim_fresh(epoch, daemon_pid, token, lease_expiry):
    """Atomically create the marker iff it does not exist (O_EXCL). Returns True if
    we won the claim. This is the actual mutex — colliding-ns front-runners cannot
    both succeed here."""
    try:
        fd = os.open(_MARKER, os.O_CREAT | os.O_EXCL | os.O_WRONLY, 0o644)
    except FileExistsError:
        return False
    except OSError:
        return False
    try:
        os.write(fd, _marker_content(epoch, daemon_pid, token, lease_expiry).encode())
        os.fsync(fd)
    finally:
        os.close(fd)
    return True


def _reap_dead_marker(m):
    """Free the holder marker the instant its daemon PID is dead — seconds-level,
    FIFO-independent reclaim (NOT gated on lease/TTL and NOT on a waiter reaching the
    front of the queue). A marker whose daemon process no longer exists can never be
    renewed or impersonated (PID reuse makes it ALIVE, not dead — see below), so it is
    pure garbage and removing it is the documented "PID death → free in seconds" path.

    Leaves a PID-*alive* holder alone: a healthy holder, a hung-but-alive daemon, and
    a stale marker whose PID was *reused* by some live process all keep `_alive` True,
    so they are governed by the lease+grace takeover path, never reaped here.

    Race-safe against a concurrent takeover that may swap in a FRESH (alive) marker:
    we rename the marker aside (atomic — exactly one reaper/takeover wins the rename),
    then delete it only after re-confirming the renamed file STILL names a dead PID; if
    we grabbed a freshly-installed live marker, we put it back untouched. Crashing
    mid-reap orphans a harmless `.reap-*` dotfile and leaves the lock FREE — the safe
    direction for a holder we already proved dead."""
    if m is None:
        return
    pid = m.get("daemon_pid", 0)
    if _alive(int(pid) if pid else 0):
        return
    aside = os.path.join(_DIR, ".reap-%d-%d" % (os.getpid(), time.time_ns()))
    try:
        os.rename(_MARKER, aside)
    except OSError:
        return  # already gone, or another reaper/takeover won the rename
    cur = _read_json(aside)
    if cur is not None and _alive(int(cur.get("daemon_pid", 0) or 0)):
        try:
            os.rename(aside, _MARKER)  # we grabbed a live marker — restore it untouched
        except OSError:
            try:
                os.remove(aside)
            except OSError:
                pass
    else:
        try:
            os.remove(aside)
        except OSError:
            pass


def _claim_or_takeover(epoch, daemon_pid, token):
    """Try to become the marker holder. Returns True on success.

    Fresh claim (no marker) is a single O_EXCL winner. Stale takeover grabs the
    stale marker with an atomic rename (exactly one racer wins the rename — the
    rest get ENOENT) and then O_EXCL-creates a new marker; if some third party
    created a fresh marker in between, our create fails and we lose cleanly. A
    *fresh* marker owned by someone else means we lost — return False (do NOT
    disturb a live holder)."""
    lease = time.time() + _LEASE
    if _claim_fresh(epoch, daemon_pid, token, lease):
        return True
    # Marker exists. Take over only if it is stale.
    m = _read_json(_MARKER)
    if not _marker_stale(m):
        return False
    # An over-cap marker may still have a LIVE daemon (the wedged-holder case the cap
    # exists for). Tell that daemon to stand down BEFORE we grab the marker, so it
    # cannot rewrite (resurrect) it mid-takeover and livelock us. A lease-stale daemon
    # has already self-fenced, so this only fires for the over-cap path. (PID reuse
    # could in theory misdirect this SIGTERM; the marker is being discarded regardless
    # and SIGTERM is recoverable — an accepted residual to bound a wedged holder.)
    if _over_abs_cap(m):
        old_pid = int(m.get("daemon_pid", 0) or 0)
        if old_pid > 0 and _alive(old_pid):
            try:
                os.kill(old_pid, signal.SIGTERM)
            except OSError:
                pass
    taking = os.path.join(_DIR, ".taking-%d-%d" % (daemon_pid, time.time_ns()))
    try:
        os.rename(_MARKER, taking)
    except OSError:
        return False  # another racer grabbed the stale marker first
    try:
        os.remove(taking)
    except OSError:
        pass
    lease = time.time() + _LEASE
    return _claim_fresh(epoch, daemon_pid, token, lease)


def _i_hold(epoch, daemon_pid):
    """Authoritative 'do I hold the lock?' check: the marker exists, names my epoch
    and daemon, and that daemon is alive."""
    m = _read_json(_MARKER)
    if m is None:
        return False
    return (
        m.get("epoch") == epoch
        and int(m.get("daemon_pid", 0)) == daemon_pid
        and _alive(daemon_pid)
    )


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# The detached holder daemon
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
_d_terminating = False
_d_last_renew = None   # monotonic time of the last agent renew (SIGUSR1)
_d_wake_w = None       # self-pipe write fd


def _d_install_signals(wake_w):
    global _d_wake_w
    _d_wake_w = wake_w

    def on_term(_sig, _frame):
        global _d_terminating
        _d_terminating = True  # flag only — file ops happen in the loop

    def on_usr1(_sig, _frame):
        global _d_last_renew
        _d_last_renew = time.monotonic()  # stamp only

    signal.signal(signal.SIGTERM, on_term)
    signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, on_term)
    signal.signal(signal.SIGUSR1, on_usr1)
    try:
        signal.signal(signal.SIGHUP, signal.SIG_IGN)
    except (ValueError, OSError):
        pass
    # Make select() return the moment any handled signal fires (PEP 475-proof).
    signal.set_wakeup_fd(wake_w)


def _d_sleep(read_fd, seconds):
    try:
        r, _, _ = select.select([read_fd], [], [], seconds)
        if r:
            try:
                os.read(read_fd, 65536)  # drain
            except OSError:
                pass
    except (OSError, select.error):
        pass


def _d_log(logf, msg):
    if logf:
        try:
            logf.write("%.3f %s\n" % (time.time(), msg))
            logf.flush()
        except OSError:
            pass


def _daemon(cfg):
    """Run as the detached holder. cfg keys: epoch, ns, token, watch_parent."""
    global _d_last_renew
    epoch = cfg["epoch"]
    ns = cfg["ns"]
    token = cfg["token"]
    watch_parent = cfg.get("watch_parent") or 0
    pid = os.getpid()

    logf = None
    if _DEBUG:
        try:
            logf = open(os.path.join(_DIR, ".daemon-%d.log" % pid), "a")
        except OSError:
            logf = None

    r_fd, w_fd = os.pipe()
    os.set_blocking(r_fd, False)
    os.set_blocking(w_fd, False)
    _d_install_signals(w_fd)

    ticket_name, ticket_path = _make_ticket(ns, pid)
    state_path = _state_path(token)

    # Take the lock. If we lose the marker race, exit so acquire re-queues.
    if not _claim_or_takeover(epoch, pid, token):
        _d_log(logf, "lost marker race at startup; exiting")
        try:
            os.remove(ticket_path)
        except OSError:
            pass
        return 0

    _write_atomic(state_path, json.dumps({
        "daemon_pid": pid, "epoch": epoch, "ticket": ticket_name, "token": token,
    }))
    _d_log(logf, "daemon holds marker (epoch=%s pid=%d)" % (epoch, pid))

    _d_last_renew = time.monotonic()

    def cleanup():
        m = _read_json(_MARKER)
        if m is not None and m.get("epoch") == epoch and int(m.get("daemon_pid", 0)) == pid:
            try:
                os.remove(_MARKER)
            except OSError:
                pass
        for p in (ticket_path, state_path):
            try:
                os.remove(p)
            except OSError:
                pass
        _d_log(logf, "cleaned up; exiting")

    while True:
        now_mono = time.monotonic()
        now_wall = time.time()

        if _d_terminating:
            _d_log(logf, "SIGTERM/release")
            cleanup()
            return 0

        # Abandonment / immortal-daemon backstops. The absolute cap is measured in
        # WALL-CLOCK time from the claim epoch — NOT monotonic from birth. Monotonic
        # can fail to advance across a macOS system sleep, which let a wedged-but-alive
        # daemon overrun the cap while still renewing its (wall-clock) lease; wall-clock
        # hold-age is sleep-proof and is the SAME quantity a waiter uses to reclaim us,
        # so daemon self-exit (at ABS_MAX) and external takeover (at ABS_MAX + GRACE)
        # can never disagree about how long we have held.
        hold_age = now_wall - epoch / 1e9
        if hold_age >= _ABS_MAX or now_mono >= _d_last_renew + _GAP:
            reason = "abs-cap" if hold_age >= _ABS_MAX else "renew-gap"
            _d_log(logf, "%s deadline (hold_age=%.0fs); releasing" % (reason, hold_age))
            cleanup()
            return 0

        # Work-progress reclaim: the held gate stamped a progress file and then
        # stopped advancing (hung pytest). Free it well before ABS_MAX. Only once the
        # file EXISTS (the gate has started) — so a long pre-gate rebase, which writes
        # no progress, is governed by GAP, not this. Keyed to gate mtime alone, NOT the
        # agent's renew, so a timer-renewing agent cannot keep a wedged gate alive.
        if _PROGRESS_FILE is not None and _PROGRESS > 0:
            try:
                pmtime = os.path.getmtime(_PROGRESS_FILE)
            except OSError:
                pmtime = None
            if pmtime is not None and (now_wall - pmtime) > _PROGRESS:
                _d_log(logf, "gate made no progress for >%ds; releasing" % _PROGRESS)
                cleanup()
                return 0

        # Legacy fast recovery: wrapping process gone.
        if watch_parent and not _alive(watch_parent):
            _d_log(logf, "watched parent %d gone; releasing" % watch_parent)
            cleanup()
            return 0

        # Did we lose the marker (taken over)? Then stop WITHOUT re-staking it.
        m = _read_json(_MARKER)
        if m is None or m.get("epoch") != epoch or int(m.get("daemon_pid", 0)) != pid:
            _d_log(logf, "marker no longer ours; exiting (no re-stake)")
            try:
                os.remove(ticket_path)
                os.remove(state_path)
            except OSError:
                pass
            return 0

        # Self-fence: if we overran our own lease we may already be reclaimable —
        # do NOT rewrite the marker (would clobber a successor). Exit instead.
        if now_wall >= float(m.get("lease_expiry", 0)):
            _d_log(logf, "overran own lease; self-fencing")
            try:
                os.remove(ticket_path)
                os.remove(state_path)
            except OSError:
                pass
            return 0

        # Healthy: renew the lease (fresh clock read, to minimise the window between
        # the self-fence check above and this write), keep the fairness ticket fresh.
        _write_atomic(_MARKER, _marker_content(epoch, pid, token, time.time() + _LEASE))
        if not os.path.exists(ticket_path):
            _make_ticket(ns, pid)  # keep our FIFO place visible to old-version waiters
        _touch(ticket_path)

        _d_sleep(r_fd, _RENEW)


def _spawn_daemon(epoch, ns, token, watch_parent):
    """Spawn the detached holder daemon; return its PID."""
    cfg = {"epoch": epoch, "ns": ns, "token": token, "watch_parent": watch_parent}
    devnull = open(os.devnull, "r+b")
    p = subprocess.Popen(
        [sys.executable, os.path.abspath(__file__), "__daemon", json.dumps(cfg)],
        stdin=devnull, stdout=devnull, stderr=devnull,
        start_new_session=True, close_fds=True,
    )
    return p.pid


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# acquire / renew / release / status
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
def _existing_live_holder(token):
    """If this worktree already holds (or is bringing up) the lock, return its
    state dict; else None. Verifies the recorded daemon is alive AND owns the
    marker, so a stale state file from a crashed prior acquire is ignored."""
    st = _read_json(_state_path(token))
    if st is None:
        return None
    dpid = int(st.get("daemon_pid", 0))
    if _alive(dpid) and _i_hold(st.get("epoch"), dpid):
        return st
    return None


def _acquire(watch_parent=0):
    """Block until we hold the lock; spawn the daemon that keeps holding it.
    Returns (ok, token). Idempotent per worktree."""
    os.makedirs(_DIR, exist_ok=True)
    token = _token()

    held = _existing_live_holder(token)
    if held is not None:
        _log("already held by this worktree (daemon PID %s); reusing" % held.get("daemon_pid"))
        return True, token

    arrival_ns = time.time_ns()
    my_pid = os.getpid()
    my_name, my_path = _make_ticket(arrival_ns, my_pid)

    waited = 0
    last_report = -_REPORT_EVERY
    while True:
        _touch(my_path)
        live = _scan()
        names = [n for _, _, n in live]
        if my_name not in names:
            _make_ticket(arrival_ns, my_pid)  # alive but reclaimed under us; re-place
            continue
        idx = names.index(my_name)

        if idx == 0:  # front of the FIFO — attempt the marker (the real mutex)
            m = _read_json(_MARKER)
            if m is None or _marker_stale(m):
                epoch = time.time_ns()
                dpid = _spawn_daemon(epoch, arrival_ns, token, watch_parent)
                if _await_daemon(token, epoch):
                    try:
                        os.remove(my_path)  # daemon has its own ticket now
                    except OSError:
                        pass
                    st = _read_json(_state_path(token)) or {}
                    extra = " after %ds" % waited if waited else ""
                    _log("lock acquired (daemon PID %s)%s; holding through "
                         "rebase → render gate → ff-merge" % (st.get("daemon_pid"), extra))
                    return True, token
                # Daemon did not confirm holding. If it merely LOST a collision race
                # it has already exited; if it is alive (slow startup) it might still
                # hold — SIGTERM it so we never leave an orphan holding while we
                # report failure, then fall through and keep waiting.
                if _alive(dpid):
                    try:
                        os.kill(dpid, signal.SIGTERM)
                    except OSError:
                        pass
            # else: someone holds a FRESH marker; just wait for them.

        if waited >= _WAIT_MAX:
            _log("waited %ds without acquiring; FAILING (not proceeding unlocked). Retry."
                 % _WAIT_MAX)
            try:
                os.remove(my_path)
            except OSError:
                pass
            return False, token

        if waited - last_report >= _REPORT_EVERY:
            mk = _read_json(_MARKER)
            hp = mk.get("daemon_pid") if mk else None
            ahead = [p for _, p, _ in live[:idx]]
            _log("waiting our turn… position %d of %d queued "
                 "(holder daemon PID %s; %ds elapsed). PIDs ahead: %s"
                 % (idx, max(0, len(live) - 1), hp, waited, ahead))
            last_report = waited
        time.sleep(_POLL)
        waited += _POLL


def _await_daemon(token, epoch):
    """Wait up to READY for the spawned daemon to actually take the marker."""
    deadline = time.monotonic() + _READY
    while time.monotonic() < deadline:
        st = _read_json(_state_path(token))
        if st is not None and st.get("epoch") == epoch:
            dpid = int(st.get("daemon_pid", 0))
            if _alive(dpid) and _i_hold(epoch, dpid):
                return True
            if not _alive(dpid):
                return False  # daemon exited (lost the marker race)
        time.sleep(0.2)
    return False


def cmd_acquire(_args):
    ok, _ = _acquire(watch_parent=0)
    return 0 if ok else 1


def cmd_renew(_args):
    token = _token()
    st = _read_json(_state_path(token))
    if st is None:
        _log("renew: no lock recorded for this worktree — nothing to renew")
        return 1
    dpid = int(st.get("daemon_pid", 0))
    epoch = st.get("epoch")
    if not (_alive(dpid) and _i_hold(epoch, dpid)):
        _log("renew: LOCK LOST (daemon gone or marker taken over) — re-acquire before merging")
        return 1
    try:
        os.kill(dpid, signal.SIGUSR1)
    except OSError as e:
        _log("renew: could not signal daemon %d (%s)" % (dpid, e))
        return 1
    _log("renewed (daemon PID %d still holds the lock)" % dpid)
    return 0


def cmd_release(_args):
    token = _token()
    st = _read_json(_state_path(token))
    if st is None:
        _log("release: nothing held by this worktree")
        return 0
    dpid = int(st.get("daemon_pid", 0))
    epoch = st.get("epoch")
    if _alive(dpid):
        try:
            os.kill(dpid, signal.SIGTERM)
        except OSError:
            pass
        # Give the daemon a moment to clean up its own marker/ticket/state.
        for _ in range(20):
            if not _alive(dpid):
                break
            time.sleep(0.1)
    # Safety net if the daemon was already dead / didn't clean up: remove the
    # marker ONLY if it is still ours (epoch+pid match — PID reuse can't match).
    m = _read_json(_MARKER)
    if m is not None and m.get("epoch") == epoch and int(m.get("daemon_pid", 0)) == dpid:
        try:
            os.remove(_MARKER)
        except OSError:
            pass
    tk = st.get("ticket")
    if tk:
        try:
            os.remove(os.path.join(_DIR, tk))
        except OSError:
            pass
    try:
        os.remove(_state_path(token))
    except OSError:
        pass
    _log("released")
    return 0


def cmd_evict(_args):
    """Force-reclaim a CONFIRMED-WEDGED holder without waiting out the ~41-min automatic
    abs-cap reclaim. Gated by `_EVICT_MIN`: refuses if the holder's hold age is under the
    floor (a healthy land can legitimately hold the lock that long), so it can never be used
    to jump a moving queue. Kills the holder's daemon, removes its marker + ticket, and frees
    the lock for the next FIFO waiter. Use only on a holder you have observed NOT advancing."""
    os.makedirs(_DIR, exist_ok=True)
    m = _read_json(_MARKER)
    if m is None:
        _log("evict: lock is free — nothing to evict")
        return 0
    now = time.time()
    age = _hold_age(m, now)
    dpid = int(m.get("daemon_pid", 0))
    if age is None:
        _log("evict: holder marker has no readable hold age — refusing")
        return 1
    if age < _EVICT_MIN:
        _log("evict: REFUSED — holder daemon PID %d hold_age=%.0fs is under the evict floor "
             "%ds. A healthy land can hold the lock this long; only evict a holder you have "
             "CONFIRMED is wedged (queue not advancing). Raise the floor or wait it out."
             % (dpid, age, _EVICT_MIN))
        return 1
    _log("evict: reclaiming wedged holder daemon PID %d (hold_age=%.0fs >= floor %ds)"
         % (dpid, age, _EVICT_MIN))
    if _alive(dpid):
        try:
            os.kill(dpid, signal.SIGKILL)
        except OSError as e:
            _log("evict: could not kill daemon %d (%s) — continuing to clear its marker" % (dpid, e))
    cur = _read_json(_MARKER)
    if cur is not None and cur.get("epoch") == m.get("epoch") and int(cur.get("daemon_pid", 0)) == dpid:
        try:
            os.remove(_MARKER)
        except OSError:
            pass
    for f in os.listdir(_DIR):
        if f.endswith("-%d" % dpid):
            try:
                os.remove(os.path.join(_DIR, f))
            except OSError:
                pass
    _log("evict: lock freed; next FIFO waiter may proceed")
    return 0


def cmd_status(_args):
    os.makedirs(_DIR, exist_ok=True)
    live = _scan()
    m = _read_json(_MARKER)
    now = time.time()
    print("merge-gate dir: %s" % _DIR)
    if m is None:
        print("holder marker: (none — lock is free)")
    else:
        age = now - float(m.get("lease_expiry", now)) + _LEASE
        hold = _hold_age(m, now)
        print("holder marker: daemon PID %s epoch %s  lease_age=%.0fs hold_age=%s "
              "alive=%s stale=%s over_cap=%s"
              % (m.get("daemon_pid"), m.get("epoch"), age,
                 ("%.0fs" % hold) if hold is not None else "?",
                 _alive(int(m.get("daemon_pid", 0))), _marker_stale(m, now),
                 _over_abs_cap(m, now)))
    if not live:
        print("fairness queue: (empty)")
    else:
        for i, (ns, pid, name) in enumerate(live):
            print("  %s %s (pid %d)" % ("HOLD/FRONT" if i == 0 else "wait %d " % i, name, pid))
    token = _token()
    st = _read_json(_state_path(token))
    if st is not None:
        print("this worktree (token %s): daemon PID %s epoch %s held=%s"
              % (token, st.get("daemon_pid"), st.get("epoch"),
                 _i_hold(st.get("epoch"), int(st.get("daemon_pid", 0)))))
    else:
        print("this worktree (token %s): not holding" % token)
    return 0


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Wrapped-command process-group cleanup (legacy + NOLOCK paths)
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# The wrapped command is typically ``bash -c 'rebase; pytest; ff-merge'`` — a heavy render
# suite. Run it in its OWN session/group and track the pgid, so a signal/exit to this wrapper
# tears down the WHOLE child tree instead of orphaning the pytest to PID 1 (the leak diagnosed
# in RESOURCE_GOVERNANCE_DIAGNOSIS.md). An un-trappable SIGKILL still orphans; bin/reap-orphan-
# gates is the backstop. (The detached holder daemon is in its own session and never a member
# of this group, so tearing the group down never disturbs the lock.)
_child_pgid = None


def _kill_child_group():
    global _child_pgid
    pgid = _child_pgid
    if pgid is None:
        return
    _child_pgid = None
    try:
        os.killpg(pgid, 0)  # any survivors? (empty group after a clean wait → nothing to do)
    except ProcessLookupError:
        return
    except OSError:
        pass
    try:
        os.killpg(pgid, signal.SIGTERM)
    except OSError:
        return
    time.sleep(0.2)
    try:
        os.killpg(pgid, signal.SIGKILL)
    except OSError:
        pass


def _run_child_group(argv):
    global _child_pgid
    p = subprocess.Popen(argv, start_new_session=True)
    try:
        _child_pgid = os.getpgid(p.pid)
    except OSError:
        _child_pgid = p.pid
    try:
        return p.wait()
    finally:
        _kill_child_group()


def _install_group_signals(extra=None):
    def handler(signum, _frame):
        _kill_child_group()
        if extra is not None:
            extra()
        signal.signal(signum, signal.SIG_DFL)
        os.kill(os.getpid(), signum)
    for sig in (signal.SIGINT, signal.SIGTERM, signal.SIGHUP):
        try:
            signal.signal(sig, handler)
        except (ValueError, OSError):
            pass
    atexit.register(_kill_child_group)


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Legacy single-command mode (back-compat): acquire → run → release in-process
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
def _legacy(argv):
    ok, token = _acquire(watch_parent=os.getpid())
    if not ok:
        _log("could not acquire the merge lock; aborting")
        return 1
    released = {"done": False}

    def do_release():
        if released["done"]:
            return
        released["done"] = True
        try:
            cmd_release(None)
        except Exception:
            pass

    atexit.register(do_release)
    _install_group_signals(extra=do_release)

    try:
        return _run_child_group(argv)
    finally:
        do_release()


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
# Entry point
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------- #
_USAGE = """usage:
  bin/with-merge-lock acquire     # block until held; spawn the holder daemon; return
  bin/with-merge-lock renew       # extend the hold AND verify we still hold (else exit 1)
  bin/with-merge-lock release     # release the lock for the next agent
  bin/with-merge-lock status      # show the holder + FIFO queue (incl. hold_age / over_cap)
  bin/with-merge-lock evict       # force-reclaim a CONFIRMED-wedged holder (gated by hold age)
  bin/with-merge-lock <cmd...>    # legacy: hold the lock while <cmd> runs, release on exit

Hold the lock across the WHOLE landing sequence:
  bin/with-merge-lock acquire
  git rebase main                 # resolve any conflicts at leisure — main is frozen
  bin/with-merge-lock renew && .venv/bin/python -m pytest -q   # render gate, exact state
  bin/with-merge-lock renew && git -C <main-checkout> merge --ff-only <branch>
  bin/with-merge-lock release
"""


def main(argv):
    if not argv:
        sys.stderr.write(_USAGE)
        return 2

    if argv[0] == "__daemon":
        try:
            cfg = json.loads(argv[1])
        except (IndexError, ValueError):
            return 2
        return _daemon(cfg)

    if argv[0] in _SUBCOMMANDS:
        if _DISABLED and argv[0] in ("acquire", "renew", "release"):
            _log("disabled (RTT_MERGE_GATE_NOLOCK=1); %s is a no-op" % argv[0])
            return 0
        return {
            "acquire": cmd_acquire,
            "renew": cmd_renew,
            "release": cmd_release,
            "status": cmd_status,
            "evict": cmd_evict,
        }[argv[0]](argv[1:])

    # Legacy: wrap a command.
    if _DISABLED:
        _log("disabled (RTT_MERGE_GATE_NOLOCK=1); running without the lock")
        _install_group_signals()
        return _run_child_group(argv)
    return _legacy(argv)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(main(sys.argv[1:]))
